docs.lead_paragraph: The speech of Lord NAPIER before the St. George's Society of New-York has not passed unper ceived or unappreciated at Paris. At a moment when the French national pride is at its zenith, the proposi tion that, to the Anglo-American race belongs the future empire of the world, falling from so important a personage as the British Minister in America, naturally excites in France a storm of bitter criticism.
